detail_description: Horseshoe Bend, located just three miles from the center of Page, Arizona, is a must-see attraction. A short half-mile hike leads to an overlook where you can capture iconic photos of the Colorado River's unique bend. Consider taking a rafting trip on the river for an even closer experience. Sunset is the ideal time to visit, as it creates stunning photo opportunities with the sun setting behind the bend.
name: Horseshoe Bend

excerpt: Lake Powell was formed by this 710-ft. concrete dam, with a visitors center & daily guided tours.
detail_description: Glen Canyon Dam, a 710-ft. concrete structure, created Lake Powell and is a popular spot for guided tours and photo opportunities. Located in Page, this town serves as a base camp for exploring iconic attractions like Horseshoe Bend, Antelope Canyon, and the Colorado River. Visitors can enjoy boat tours from the foot of the dam, drifting through Horseshoe Bend and anchoring at Petroglyph Beach before returning to Page via motorcoach.
name: Glen Canyon Dam

excerpt: Page is a city in Coconino County, Arizona, United States, near the Glen Canyon Dam and Lake Powell. As of the 2010 census, the population of the city was 7,247. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Page, a city in Coconino County, Arizona, is located near the Glen Canyon Dam and Lake Powell. With a population of around 7,247 people as of the 2010 census, it's a small town on the edge of Navajo Nation and Lake Powell. While previously known as just a stopover for travelers heading to or from the Grand Canyon or Horseshoe Bend, Page has been expanding to meet the growing demand from visitors using it as a base.
name: Page

detail_description: The Carl Hayden Visitor Center, a circular glass-enclosed observation building, is perched 110 feet above the Glen Canyon Dam. This modernistic structure was completed in 1963 to accommodate and educate tourists visiting Lake Powell. Inside, visitors can explore interpretive exhibits on area geology and history as well as an enlightening relief map.
name: Carl Hayden Visitor Center

detail_description: Glen Canyon National Recreation Area is a stunning destination featuring Lake Powell and a stretch of the Colorado River. Visitors can enjoy float trips from Glen Canyon Dam to Lees Ferry, operated by Wilderness River Adventures. The Carl Hayden Visitor Center offers panoramic views of the dam and interactive displays. Horseshoe Bend, formed by the Colorado River, is another popular attraction in the area.
name: Glen Canyon National Recreation Area
address: 691 Scenic View Rd Dr, Page, AZ 86040, USA

excerpt: Chill BBQ joint with a retro vibe slinging brisket & other slow-smoked eats in a former gas station.
detail_description: Big John's Texas BBQ is a laid-back barbecue spot with a nostalgic atmosphere, located in a renovated gas station. The restaurant exudes an old-school American vibe with its simple wooden tables and chairs, linoleum floors, and fluorescent lighting. Specializing in slow-smoked meats like brisket, pulled pork, sausage, ribs, and chicken, the menu offers various ways to enjoy them - from sandwiches to combo plates with sides like cornbread muffins and coleslaw.
name: Big John's Texas BBQ
address: 153 S Lake Powell Blvd, Page, AZ 86040, USA

excerpt: A short hike down a set of rock-carved stairs leads to this viewpoint on the rim of the river & dam.
detail_description: Glen Canyon Dam Overlook is a popular spot in Page, Arizona, offering a short and easy hike down to a viewpoint along the rim of Glen Canyon. It takes about 20 minutes to reach the overlook, where visitors can enjoy stunning views of the river and dam. The overlook features rock-carved stairs and a parking lot for convenience. Nearby attractions include Waterhole Canyon, known for its beautiful slot canyons and gorges cutting through Navajo red sandstone.
name: Glen Canyon Dam Overlook

excerpt: Museum commemorating the leader of the first Colorado River exploration through the Grand Canyon.
detail_description: The John Wesley Powell Museum, situated in downtown Page and operated by the local visitors bureau, is a must-visit spot. It offers free admission for families and showcases the history of Colorado River exploration, including information on explorers, local tribes, geology and dinosaurs. The museum also features a trading post where one can purchase souvenirs. Visitors may learn about John Powell's journey through the Grand Canyon at this museum with informative exhibits that even feature items like his bed frame from Maine.
name: Powell Museum & Archives
address: 6 N Lake Powell Blvd, Page, AZ 86040, USA

detail_description: Lower Antelope Canyon is a must-see experience that offers unique and breathtaking views. The canyon, where giant rock walls enclose the path, creates a sense of wonder as you navigate through its curves. One way to explore it is by renting a foot pedaling kayak from the Marina and paddling around to Lower Antelope Canyon. Along the way, there are checkpoints including climbing ladders and boulders.
name: Lower Antelope Canyon

excerpt: Navajo heritage center offering tours of a traditional home site, dancing & cultural programs.
detail_description: Step into the world of the Navajo people at the Navajo Village Heritage Center, a charming and family-run facility that offers tours of traditional home sites, cultural programs, and dance demonstrations. This immersive experience provides insights into the traditional way of life and unique features of Navajo homes. Visitors can also explore the culture and heritage of the Navajo people through engaging storytelling and presentations.
name: Navajo Village Heritage Center

detail_description: When visiting Page, Arizona, make sure to stop by Grand Canyon Brewing + Distillery for a refreshing experience. This establishment offers a wide selection of craft beers and other drinks, making it the perfect place to unwind after a day of desert exploration. With multiple locations across Arizona and its own distillery, Grand Canyon Brewing is a must-visit for craft beer enthusiasts. Whether you're into classic IPAs or unique fruit-infused ales, there's something for everyone to enjoy here.
name: Grand Canyon Brewing +Distillery
address: 714 N Navajo Dr, Page, AZ 86040, USA

detail_description: Page Municipal Airport is a small and friendly airport located in Page, Arizona. The airport offers excellent views for travelers flying in and out of the area. It's worth noting that Arizona does not observe daylight savings time, but the nearby Navajo Nation does. This means that during the summer, there may be a time difference when traveling outside of Page. The airport provides convenient services such as free parking and 24-hour front desk assistance with fax service.
name: Page Municipal Airport

detail_description: The New Wave, also known as the Beehive Trail, is a stunning sandstone formation located near Page, Arizona. Unlike its more popular counterpart, The Wave at Coyote Buttes, no permit is required to visit this beautiful spot. The hike to the New Wave is relatively easy and short compared to other trails in the area. This makes it an accessible and enjoyable experience for visitors year-round. The area is home to various breathtaking rock formations that showcase the natural beauty of the Arizona desert.
name: The New Wave

detail_description: Glen Canyon Dam Bridge, located in the young town of Page, Arizona, was built in 1957 to retain water from the upper Colorado River and generate hydroelectric power for the region. Despite environmental controversies surrounding large dams, the engineering marvel of Glen Canyon Dam is undeniably impressive. The dam offers a picturesque setting and serves as a popular tourist stop. Visitors can enjoy breathtaking views of the Colorado River below and explore the nearby museum to learn about its history and significance.
name: Glen Canyon Dam Bridge

excerpt: 1-mile hiking loop in Glen Canyon leading to a luxuriant garden nestled in the mesa's sandstone.
detail_description: The Hanging Garden Trailhead is a family-friendly 1.2-mile hiking loop near Page, Arizona, offering stunning views of the surrounding landscape and beautiful lake views. The trail leads to a lush oasis in the desert with colorful wildflowers and an abundance of vegetation. It's accessible year-round and provides an interesting overview of the area.
name: Hanging Garden Trailhead

excerpt: Basic American eatery known for dishing out homestyle breakfast faves, plus chicken fried steak.
detail_description: Ranch House Grille is a classic American eatery that specializes in serving up traditional homestyle breakfast favorites and hearty southwestern comfort food. Located conveniently near the Page Municipal Airport, it's a popular stop for tourists heading to top attractions. The restaurant offers generous portions of dishes like corned beef hash, country fried steak, and eggs while providing a friendly atmosphere where owners love to engage in local gossip with patrons.
name: Ranch House Grille
address: 819 N Navajo Dr, Page, AZ 86040, USA

detail_description: Horseshoe Bend Overlook Parking Lot is a must-visit spot along the North Rim Scenic Drive to Cape Royal. The $10 entry fee is worth it for the stunning views and well-maintained walking trail. Although parking can be pricey, the approximately 1.5-mile round trip offers a pilgrimage through breathtaking landscapes. It's a rare piece of natural beauty that's definitely worth the stop, especially if you're en route to Page for another tour.
name: Horseshoe Bend Overlook Parking Lot

excerpt: Historic park along the Tallapoosa River known for hiking, boating & Andrew Jackson's Creek War win.
detail_description: Horseshoe Bend is a historic park along the Tallapoosa River, offering activities such as hiking and boating. It holds significance for being the site of Andrew Jackson's Creek War win. Situated below the Glen Canyon Dam, it marks the point where the Colorado River continues its journey towards the Grand Canyon.
name: Horseshoe Bend

detail_description: Page Lake Powell Campground is a popular destination in Page, AZ, offering a wide range of activities for visitors. Located near the Glen Canyon Dam, it provides easy access to Lake Powell where visitors can enjoy kayaking, fishing, paddle-boarding, and swimming. The campground offers facilities for both RVs and tents and is conveniently situated close to Horseshoe Bend. Additionally, its proximity to national parks, Navajo land, and historic sites makes it an ideal base for exploring the Southwest.
name: Page Lake Powell Campground

excerpt: Snug red-rock canyon sculpted into flowing forms mainly by flooding, now explorable on foot.
detail_description: Ken's Tours Lower Antelope Canyon is a popular destination for both locals and tourists, offering scenic red-rock formations sculpted by flooding. Visitors can explore the canyon on foot with guided tours and capture stunning photographs. The tour company provides an efficient reservation process and enforces the Navajo Nation's mask mandate. With knowledgeable guides sharing historical stories, visitors can navigate through tight spaces, ladders, and stairs to enjoy breathtaking views.
name: Ken's Tours Lower Antelope Canyon

excerpt: Picturesque natural attraction featuring red-rock canyons with unique shapes & formations.
detail_description: Dixie's Lower Antelope Canyon Tours is a must-visit natural attraction in Page, Arizona. The red-rock canyons with unique shapes and formations offer a picturesque experience for adventurers and nature lovers. The agency offers two spectacular sightseeing tours that are educational, informational, and breathtaking. Visitors highly recommend the guided tour as it provides an unforgettable experience with knowledgeable guides who offer photography tips and ensure great photo opportunities.
name: Dixie's Lower Antelope Canyon Tours

detail_description: Lake Powell Paddleboards and Kayaks is a family-owned rental service in Page, Arizona, offering paddleboard, kayak, and canoe rentals for visitors to explore the breathtaking Lake Powell. The tours are led by PSUPA Certified guides who provide an enjoyable experience. Additionally, visitors can also check out Kayak Powell for official kayak rentals on the lake. The area offers various activities such as float trips from Glen Canyon Dam to Lees Ferry operated by Wilderness River Adventures from March through early December.
name: Lake Powell Paddleboards and Kayaks

excerpt: Easygoing outlet providing an extensive menu of Jalisco-style offerings in a colorful setting.
detail_description: Fiesta Mexicana Restaurant in Page, Arizona is a vibrant and casual dining spot offering an extensive menu of Jalisco-style dishes. The restaurant boasts a colorful and festive atmosphere, complete with complimentary chips and salsa. The portions are generous, with options for vegans such as veggie fajitas, burritos, avocado salad, and black bean tostadas. Guests can also enjoy strong margaritas while soaking in the cheerful decor on the patio.
name: Fiesta Mexicana Restaurant
address: 125 S Lake Powell Blvd, Page, AZ 86040, USA

excerpt: Navajo tacos made with fry bread & traditional Native American dancing are the draw at this eatery.
detail_description: Into the Grand offers a captivating experience filled with Native American song, music, dance, and authentic cuisine in an old warehouse setting. The venue's charm perfectly complements the evening's essence. Located near Horseshoe Bend and Waterhole Canyon, it provides a unique cultural experience. While only open during the summer, this buffet dinner and dance performance is worth visiting for an immersive encounter with Navajo culture.
name: Into the Grand

detail_description: Discover the breathtaking beauty of The Wave, a mesmerizing rock formation located within the expansive and pristine Vermilion Cliffs National Monument. This remote and untouched marvel spans over 280,000 acres and is home to Coyote Buttes North, where The Wave's stunning swirling terracotta and alabaster hues captivate visitors. While reaching this natural wonder requires a challenging 6.4-mile round trip hike, the awe-inspiring views at the end make it an unforgettable experience for nature enthusiasts.
name: The Wave
address: 644 N Navajo Dr, Page, AZ 86040, USA

excerpt: Layers of red rocks display clear stratifications at this designated national monument.
detail_description: Vermilion Cliffs National Monument is a renowned historical landmark situated in Northern Arizona. The site showcases magnificent layers of crimson rocks with distinct stratifications, offering a glimpse into the region's geological history. Access to the monument involves traveling on a challenging gravel road, and visitors exploring wilderness areas must obtain permits. With remarkable turn-offs, bonus roads, and panoramic sights to behold, the Vermilion Cliffs National Monument caters to 4x4 enthusiasts seeking thrilling off-road experiences.
name: Vermilion Cliffs National Monument

detail_description: Located just a short drive from the Glen Canyon Dam, Wahweap Overlook is a must-visit vista point when exploring Page or Lake Powell. The overlook offers an incredible view of the beautiful rock formations in Arizona and Utah, making it a perfect spot to witness the stunning scenery at sunset or sunrise. With its large parking area, it's easily accessible for visitors.
name: Wahweap Overlook

excerpt: Barren reservation area with dramatic sandstone slot canyons.
detail_description: Waterholes Canyon is a region of arid reservation land featuring stunning sandstone slot canyons. The area is relatively uninhabited, providing visitors with a peaceful and secluded environment to explore the natural beauty of the canyons. The hike through the slot canyons is an amazing experience, offering breathtaking views of the unique rock formations and exquisite lighting. Tour groups are not typically overcrowded, allowing for an intimate exploration where visitors never feel rushed or pressured to move quickly through the tour.
name: Waterholes Canyon

detail_description: Golliard Park is a popular public park that offers various outdoor activities and relaxation opportunities. The park features a playground, swing sets, an unmarked baseball diamond for sports enthusiasts, and two fenced dog parks for four-legged companions to socialize and play off-leash. It is well-maintained with picnic tables, grills, and shaded areas for family gatherings. Additionally, the park has clean restrooms but visitors may prefer changing babies in their vehicles due to cleanliness concerns.
name: Golliard's Park
